title = "Surface Treatment Overview: Purposes and Categories"

content = """
Surface treatments modify the outer surface of a metal component to improve one or more properties—corrosion resistance, wear resistance, appearance, adhesion, electrical conductivity, or lubricity—without significantly altering the bulk material properties or dimensions. At Ridgecrest Metalworks, surface treatment is a planned final step in the production sequence for many part families.

The purposes of surface treatment include corrosion protection (the most common reason—applying a barrier or sacrificial coating to prevent oxidation and chemical attack), wear and friction control (hard coatings for abrasion resistance; low-friction coatings for moving parts), appearance and aesthetics (decorative plating, anodizing, painting for visual and marketing requirements), adhesion improvement (surface preparation and conversion coatings that improve adhesion of subsequent paint, adhesive, or rubber bonding), and functional electrical properties (conductive coatings for electrical contact, insulating coatings for electrical isolation, or EMI shielding).

Surface treatment categories at Ridgecrest include: electrochemical processes (electroplating, anodizing, electroless plating—use electrical or chemical reactions to deposit or convert the surface); thermal spray (high-temperature particle deposition of metals, ceramics, or cermets onto the substrate), organic coatings (liquid paint, powder coating, e-coat—polymer films applied and cured on the surface); conversion coatings (phosphating, chromate conversion, passivation—chemical reactions that convert the metal surface into a coating layer chemically bonded to the substrate); and physical/chemical vapor deposition (PVD, CVD—vacuum processes depositing very thin, hard films for tool coatings and precision components).

Surface treatment selection must consider: base material compatibility (not all coatings adhere to all metals), required performance (corrosion hours in salt spray per ASTM B117, hardness, adhesion, thickness), dimensional effect (plating adds thickness—tight tolerance features must allow for this), post-treatment handling and storage (some coatings are fragile until cured; some require special packaging to prevent contact damage), and environmental/regulatory compliance (hexavalent chromium, cadmium, and other regulated substances require special handling, permitting, and waste disposal).
"""

version = "0.0.1"
